#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:6
msgid "Cache: working with cross-testrun state"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:11
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:13
msgid ""
"The plugin provides two command line options to rerun failures from the last "
"``pytest`` invocation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:16
msgid "``--lf``, ``--last-failed`` - to only re-run the failures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:17
msgid ""
"``--ff``, ``--failed-first`` - to run the failures first and then the rest "
"of the tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:20
msgid ""
"For cleanup (usually not needed), a ``--cache-clear`` option allows to "
"remove all cross-session cache contents ahead of a test run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:23
msgid ""
"Other plugins may access the `config.cache`_ object to set/get **json "
"encodable** values between ``pytest`` invocations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:28
msgid ""
"This plugin is enabled by default, but can be disabled if needed: see :ref:"
"`cmdunregister` (the internal name for this plugin is ``cacheprovider``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:34
msgid "Rerunning only failures or failures first"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:36
msgid "First, let's create 50 test invocation of which only 2 fail::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:38
msgid ""
"# content of test_50.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"def test_num(i):\n"
"    if i in (17, 25):\n"
"       pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:46
msgid "If you run this for the first time you will see two failures::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:48
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q\n"
".................F.......F........................                   [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_______________________________ test_num[17] "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"i = 17\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"_______________________________ test_num[25] "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"i = 25\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"2 failed, 48 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:75
msgid "If you then run it with ``--lf``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:77
msgid ""
"$ pytest --lf\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 50 items / 48 deselected\n"
"run-last-failure: rerun previous 2 failures\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py FF                                                        [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_______________________________ test_num[17] "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"i = 17\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"_______________________________ test_num[25] "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"i = 25\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"================= 2 failed, 48 deselected in 0.12 seconds =================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:111
msgid ""
"You have run only the two failing test from the last run, while 48 tests "
"have not been run (\"deselected\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:114
msgid ""
"Now, if you run with the ``--ff`` option, all tests will be run but the "
"first previous failures will be executed first (as can be seen from the "
"series of ``FF`` and dots)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:118
msgid ""
"$ pytest --ff\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 50 items\n"
"run-last-failure: rerun previous 2 failures first\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py FF................................................        [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_______________________________ test_num[17] "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"i = 17\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"_______________________________ test_num[25] "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"i = 25\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"=================== 2 failed, 48 passed in 0.12 seconds ===================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:154
msgid ""
"New ``--nf``, ``--new-first`` options: run new tests first followed by the "
"rest of the tests, in both cases tests are also sorted by the file modified "
"time, with more recent files coming first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:159
msgid "Behavior when no tests failed in the last run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:161
msgid ""
"When no tests failed in the last run, or when no cached ``lastfailed`` data "
"was found, ``pytest`` can be configured either to run all of the tests or no "
"tests, using the ``--last-failed-no-failures`` option, which takes one of "
"the following values::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:165
msgid ""
"pytest --last-failed --last-failed-no-failures all    # run all tests "
"(default behavior)\n"
"pytest --last-failed --last-failed-no-failures none   # run no tests and exit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:169
msgid "The new config.cache object"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:173
msgid ""
"Plugins or conftest.py support code can get a cached value using the pytest "
"``config`` object.  Here is a basic example plugin which implements a :ref:"
"`fixture` which re-uses previously created state across pytest invocations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:178
msgid ""
"# content of test_caching.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import time\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def mydata(request):\n"
"    val = request.config.cache.get(\"example/value\", None)\n"
"    if val is None:\n"
"        time.sleep(9*0.6) # expensive computation :)\n"
"        val = 42\n"
"        request.config.cache.set(\"example/value\", val)\n"
"    return val\n"
"\n"
"def test_function(mydata):\n"
"    assert mydata == 23"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:194
msgid ""
"If you run this command once, it will take a while because of the sleep::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:197 ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:214
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q\n"
"F                                                                    [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"______________________________ test_function "
"_______________________________\n"
"\n"
"mydata = 42\n"
"\n"
"    def test_function(mydata):\n"
">       assert mydata == 23\n"
"E       assert 42 == 23\n"
"\n"
"test_caching.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"1 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:211
msgid ""
"If you run it a second time the value will be retrieved from the cache and "
"this will be quick::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:228
msgid "See the :ref:`cache-api` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:232
msgid "Inspecting Cache content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:234
msgid ""
"You can always peek at the content of the cache using the ``--cache-show`` "
"command line option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:237
msgid ""
"$ pytest --cache-show\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"cachedir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/.pytest_cache\n"
"------------------------------- cache values "
"-------------------------------\n"
"cache/lastfailed contains:\n"
"  {'test_caching.py::test_function': True}\n"
"cache/nodeids contains:\n"
"  ['test_caching.py::test_function']\n"
"cache/stepwise contains:\n"
"  []\n"
"example/value contains:\n"
"  42\n"
"\n"
"======================= no tests ran in 0.12 seconds ======================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:255
msgid "Clearing Cache content"
msgstr "清除快取內容"

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:257
msgid ""
"You can instruct pytest to clear all cache files and values by adding the "
"``--cache-clear`` option like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:260
msgid "pytest --cache-clear"
msgstr "pytest --cache-clear"

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:262
msgid ""
"This is recommended for invocations from Continuous Integration servers "
"where isolation and correctness is more important than speed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:268
msgid "Stepwise"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:270
msgid ""
"As an alternative to ``--lf -x``, especially for cases where you expect a "
"large part of the test suite will fail, ``--sw``, ``--stepwise`` allows you "
"to fix them one at a time. The test suite will run until the first failure "
"and then stop. At the next invocation, tests will continue from the last "
"failing test and then run until the next failing test. You may use the ``--"
"stepwise-skip`` option to ignore one failing test and stop the test "
"execution on the second failing test instead. This is useful if you get "
"stuck on a failing test and just want to ignore it until later."
msgstr ""
